 He discusses fruitful interactions with the work of scholars and colleagues that include the British anthropologist Mary Douglas and the French theorist Michel Foucault, and offers fascinating snapshots of such far-flung places as colonial Sudan, midcentury Oxford, and prerevolutionary Iran. With Journeys of the Mind, Brown offers an essential account of the “grand endeavor” to reimagine a decisive historical moment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aBrown, Peter,-1935-. 0aHistorians-United States-Biography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh  aAlbigensian Crusade.  aAugustine of Hippo.  aAxial Age.  aBradt Travel Guides.  aByzantine Empire.  aCommodus.  aContexts.  aCounter-Reformation.  aCritical philosophy.  aCrusades.  aCulture and Society.  aDe Inventione.  aDisenchantment.  aDonatism.  aErnst Gombrich.  aErudition.  aEssay.  aEvocation.  aExegesis.  aFernand Braudel.  aForay.  aForm of life (philosophy).  aGod.  aHagarism.  aJargon.  aKurt Weitzmann.  aLate Antiquity.  aLecture.  aManichaeism.  aMetaphysics.  aMithraism.  aMoralia.  aMy Tutor.  aNeurosis.  aNew Course.  aOf Education.  aPelagianism.  aPhilosopher.  aPhilosophy.  aPlotinus.  aPolitique.  aPredestination.  aProcession.  aProfumo affair.  aPuritans.  aRecusancy.  aReligion.  aRenunciation.  aRomanticism.  aSasanian Empire.  aScholarship Examination.  aScholasticism.  aSirach.  aSociety for Creative Anachronism.  aSocratic Club.  aSources of the Self.  aState formation.  aTerm logic.  aThe Dissertation.  aThe Historian's Craft.  aThe History of Sexuality.  aThe Interpretation of Dreams.  aThe Philosopher.  aThe Problem of Pain.  aThe Sufis.  aThe Two Cultures.  aThe Various.  aThought.  aTranscendent